[http://www.flickr.com/photos/pellethepoet] Goodness,  you've had another late night on this.  Good work!  I loved that mention of &quot;sea songs&quot; in the article - I imagine it was normal practice to sing in rhythm to help the work along. 

This article SMH 11/2/1876 p.6 - <a href="http://trove.nla.gov.au/ndp/del/article/13368161" rel="nofollow">trove.nla.gov.au/ndp/del/article/13368161</a> - mentions (in the second column) huge detail of the event.  Ships were HIBERNIA, EDINBURGH, and the steam tug MYSTERY.  &quot;After the cable had been safely landed, the Government steamer Ajax hove in sight off Botany, and arrived in time to congratulate the electricians upon the success of their work so far as it had gone ... ... &quot;

Fascinatingly, the same article prints several telegraphic cables received over the next few days with details of the position of the ship and progress.  The NSW end was connected and working!  Obvious really, they would have tested for faults on the way.
